1
00:00:05,083 --> 00:00:06,834
PICARD:
Commander Riker,
report to the Bridge.

2
00:00:06,834 --> 00:00:08,083
On the way.

3
00:00:09,208 --> 00:00:11,333
MAN:
Harry, Harry,
come back here!

4
00:00:11,333 --> 00:00:14,709
(<i> grunts</i> )

5
00:00:14,709 --> 00:00:16,625
What's your hurry, Harry?

6
00:00:16,625 --> 00:00:19,041
Oops.
Sorry, Commander.

7
00:00:19,041 --> 00:00:20,166
I was just...

8
00:00:20,166 --> 00:00:23,583
Harry!

9
00:00:23,583 --> 00:00:25,250
I'm sorry
if he bothered you.

10
00:00:25,250 --> 00:00:27,291
No bother,
Dr. Bernard.

11
00:00:27,291 --> 00:00:30,083
I'm not
going back.

12
00:00:30,083 --> 00:00:32,000
I hate that teacher,
and I hate calculus.

13
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:34,208
Everyone needs
an understanding
of basic calculus--

14
00:00:34,208 --> 00:00:35,667
whether they
like it or not.

15
00:00:35,667 --> 00:00:37,166
Why?

16
00:00:47,417 --> 00:00:49,041
(<i> console beeping</i> )

17
00:00:53,792 --> 00:00:55,250
BEVERLY:
You're limping.

18
00:00:55,250 --> 00:00:57,542
I had a small run-in
with an aspiring sprinter.

19
00:00:57,542 --> 00:00:58,500
Number One.

20
00:00:58,500 --> 00:00:59,542
Problem, Captain?

21
00:00:59,542 --> 00:01:00,667
More a curiosity.

22
00:01:00,667 --> 00:01:01,959
For the past few hours

23
00:01:01,959 --> 00:01:03,291
we've been tracking
faint energy readings

24
00:01:03,291 --> 00:01:05,291
in an attempt
to locate its source.

25
00:01:05,291 --> 00:01:07,625
It's like following
a trail of bread crumbs.

26
00:01:07,625 --> 00:01:10,375
The path finally led us here
and then stopped--

27
00:01:10,375 --> 00:01:13,959
which is what I knew
would interest you.

28
00:01:13,959 --> 00:01:15,291
What's our position, Geordi?

29
00:01:15,291 --> 00:01:18,625
The Epsilon
Mynos system, sir.

30
00:01:18,625 --> 00:01:19,917
RIKER:
Thank you, Captain.
you're right.

31
00:01:19,917 --> 00:01:21,583
I wouldn't miss this
for anything.

32
00:01:21,583 --> 00:01:24,250
What's so interesting
about this system?

33
00:01:24,250 --> 00:01:27,375
Aldea.

34
00:01:27,375 --> 00:01:29,834
Tasha, I'm surprised you haven't
heard the stories of Aldea--

35
00:01:29,834 --> 00:01:32,625
the wondrous,
mythical world

36
00:01:32,625 --> 00:01:34,125
like Atlantis
of ancient Earth

37
00:01:34,125 --> 00:01:36,166
or Neinman of Xerxes VII--

38
00:01:36,166 --> 00:01:40,709
advanced culture, centuries old,
self-contained, peaceful

39
00:01:40,709 --> 00:01:42,583
incredible technical
sophistication

40
00:01:42,583 --> 00:01:44,875
providing the daily
needs of all the citizens

41
00:01:44,875 --> 00:01:46,250
so that they could turn
themselves over

42
00:01:46,250 --> 00:01:48,291
to art and culture.

43
00:01:48,291 --> 00:01:49,625
Where's it
supposed to be?

44
00:01:49,625 --> 00:01:50,834
That's the myth.

45
00:01:50,834 --> 00:01:52,834
Somehow, as the legend goes

46
00:01:52,834 --> 00:01:54,625
the Aldeans were
able to cloak

47
00:01:54,625 --> 00:01:56,125
their planet
in darkness

48
00:01:56,125 --> 00:01:58,125
and go unseen
by marauders

49
00:01:58,125 --> 00:01:59,917
and other
hostile passersby

50
00:01:59,917 --> 00:02:01,875
who might rob
and plunder.

51
00:02:03,208 --> 00:02:05,458
YAR:
What a wonderful
fairy tale.

52
00:02:05,458 --> 00:02:07,667
Scanners still show
nothing, sir.

53
00:02:07,667 --> 00:02:08,959
Scanners may
show nothing, sir

54
00:02:08,959 --> 00:02:12,166
but I'm sensing
something very strong--

55
00:02:12,166 --> 00:02:13,792
thousands of minds.

56
00:02:13,792 --> 00:02:16,375
From where?

57
00:02:16,375 --> 00:02:17,792
Very close.

58
00:02:24,542 --> 00:02:27,792
All stop
and hold this position.

59
00:02:27,792 --> 00:02:29,583
Aye, sir.

60
00:02:29,583 --> 00:02:31,375
All stop

61
00:02:31,375 --> 00:02:32,667
and hold.

62
00:02:34,417 --> 00:02:36,417
Anything?

63
00:02:36,417 --> 00:02:38,375
Captain, I'm recording
a distortion

64
00:02:38,375 --> 00:02:41,667
in Quadrant 1, mark, 9-0.

65
00:02:41,667 --> 00:02:43,166
On screen.

66
00:02:43,166 --> 00:02:46,083
(<i> screen beeps</i> )

67
00:02:46,083 --> 00:02:47,375
Shields and
deflectors up.

68
00:02:47,375 --> 00:02:49,000
Aye, sir.
(<i> console beeps</i> )

69
00:03:07,750 --> 00:03:10,250
It's Aldea, Captain.

70
00:03:10,250 --> 00:03:11,834
It has to be.

71
00:03:33,208 --> 00:03:37,750
<i>Space, the final frontier.</i>

72
00:03:37,750 --> 00:03:42,083
<i>These are the voyages</i>
<i>of the Starship</i> Enterprise.

73
00:03:42,083 --> 00:03:43,667
<i>Its continuing mission--</i>

74
00:03:43,667 --> 00:03:47,750
<i>to explore</i>
<i>strange new worlds</i>

75
00:03:47,750 --> 00:03:52,417
<i>to seek out new life</i>
<i>and new civilizations</i>

76
00:03:52,417 --> 00:03:55,959
<i>to boldly go</i>
<i>where no one has gone before.</i>

77
00:04:58,792 --> 00:05:02,792
<i>Captain's Log,</i>
<i>Stardate 41509.1:</i>

78
00:05:02,792 --> 00:05:05,125
<i>Either by chance or intent</i>

79
00:05:05,125 --> 00:05:07,333
<i>we've been led</i>
<i>to the planet Aldea</i>

80
00:05:07,333 --> 00:05:08,959
<i>which appeared out of nowhere</i>

81
00:05:08,959 --> 00:05:12,125
<i>hidden behind a sophisticated</i>
<i>shielding device.</i>

82
00:05:12,125 --> 00:05:16,417
Sensors indicate
that the shield is
electromagnetic--

83
00:05:16,417 --> 00:05:19,750
a complicated light-
refracting mechanism.

84
00:05:19,750 --> 00:05:20,834
A cloaking device.

85
00:05:20,834 --> 00:05:21,917
Aye, sir.

86
00:05:21,917 --> 00:05:23,125
It's got to be
pretty sophisticated

87
00:05:23,125 --> 00:05:25,125
to hide
an entire planet.

88
00:05:25,125 --> 00:05:27,333
We're being
scanned, sir.

89
00:05:27,333 --> 00:05:29,333
Hmm. We'll let them know
our peaceful intention.

90
00:05:29,333 --> 00:05:31,417
Open hailing frequencies,
Lieutenant Yar.

91
00:05:31,417 --> 00:05:34,500
Frequencies open, sir.

92
00:05:34,500 --> 00:05:36,166
I am Rashella.

93
00:05:36,166 --> 00:05:37,375
Welcome to Aldea.

94
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:43,583
I, uh...
(<i> clears throat</i> )

95
00:05:43,583 --> 00:05:47,875
I am Jean-Luc Picard,
Captain of the USS<i> Enterprise.</i>

96
00:05:47,875 --> 00:05:49,792
We come in peace.

97
00:05:49,792 --> 00:05:51,667
We know.

98
00:05:51,667 --> 00:05:53,458
We've heard stories about Aldea

99
00:05:53,458 --> 00:05:58,333
but, frankly, I never
believed they could be true.

100
00:05:58,333 --> 00:06:00,375
Our shield has confused
outsiders

101
00:06:00,375 --> 00:06:02,792
for millennia, Captain.

102
00:06:02,792 --> 00:06:06,667
That's a very long time
to have such technology.

103
00:06:06,667 --> 00:06:09,333
Why do you reveal
yourselves to us now?

104
00:06:09,333 --> 00:06:12,000
We are eager to meet in person
to discuss that

105
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:15,250
and other subjects
of mutual interest.

106
00:06:15,250 --> 00:06:16,875
We're ready anytime.

107
00:06:16,875 --> 00:06:18,250
Excellent.

108
00:06:18,250 --> 00:06:23,000
(<i> screen beeps off,</i>
<i>alarm sounds</i> )

109
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:27,375
We mean no harm.

110
00:06:29,333 --> 00:06:32,250
Our arrival seems
to have startled you.

111
00:06:32,250 --> 00:06:34,000
It was a little sudden.

112
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:35,000
I'm Radue--

113
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:36,834
First Appointee
to Aldea.

114
00:06:36,834 --> 00:06:38,291
Welcome aboard.

115
00:06:38,291 --> 00:06:41,000
Captain, they haven't been
through decontamination.

116
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:42,166
PICARD:
Our medical doctor
is concerned

117
00:06:42,166 --> 00:06:43,291
that you didn't
go through

118
00:06:43,291 --> 00:06:45,667
the regular transporting
procedure.

119
00:06:45,667 --> 00:06:47,458
You couldn't
transport us.

120
00:06:47,458 --> 00:06:50,083
The only way through
our shield is our way, Captain.

121
00:06:50,083 --> 00:06:51,834
Our cloaking
device may be off

122
00:06:51,834 --> 00:06:55,291
but our shield
is operating.

123
00:06:55,291 --> 00:06:58,083
We've brought you
small tokens of welcome.

124
00:06:58,083 --> 00:06:59,667
And a personal
invitation

125
00:06:59,667 --> 00:07:01,458
to a celebration
on Aldea.

126
00:07:01,458 --> 00:07:03,208
That would be
delightful.

127
00:07:03,208 --> 00:07:05,709
Number One,
assemble the away team.

128
00:07:05,709 --> 00:07:06,959
We will prepare

129
00:07:06,959 --> 00:07:11,041
for your arrival,
Commander Riker.

130
00:07:11,041 --> 00:07:12,041
How do you know...?

131
00:07:12,041 --> 00:07:13,667
...your name?

132
00:07:13,667 --> 00:07:17,542
Well, we've been monitoring
your ship's communications.

133
00:07:17,542 --> 00:07:19,375
We must now
return to Aldea.

134
00:07:19,375 --> 00:07:22,542
Our eyes are very sensitive
to the bright light.

135
00:07:22,542 --> 00:07:24,208
Rashella.

136
00:07:24,208 --> 00:07:25,667
(<i> device beeping</i> )

137
00:07:29,583 --> 00:07:31,208
Amazing!

138
00:07:31,208 --> 00:07:34,208
To exist only
in that dream world of mythology

139
00:07:34,208 --> 00:07:36,667
and then suddenly to be here,
right in front of us.

140
00:07:36,667 --> 00:07:38,917
Now we know
who placed the bread crumbs.

141
00:07:38,917 --> 00:07:40,542
We're not here by accident.

142
00:07:40,542 --> 00:07:42,291
Counselor,
do you sense anything?

143
00:07:42,291 --> 00:07:46,667
They want something from us--
something we value greatly--

144
00:07:46,667 --> 00:07:50,667
so much, that they're afraid
we won't part with it.

145
00:07:50,667 --> 00:07:52,291
(<i> communications beep</i> )

146
00:07:52,291 --> 00:07:54,667
RADUE:
We're ready to receive you,
Commander Riker

147
00:07:54,667 --> 00:07:55,959
and two of your colleagues.

148
00:08:00,125 --> 00:08:04,750
Interesting choices.

149
00:08:07,041 --> 00:08:09,208
I hope that Duana and I
know how

150
00:08:09,208 --> 00:08:11,291
to greet you properly,
Commander.

151
00:08:17,750 --> 00:08:19,291
How do they
cloak the planet?

152
00:08:19,291 --> 00:08:20,917
The theory is simple--

153
00:08:20,917 --> 00:08:23,667
the shield bends light rays
around the planet's contour--

154
00:08:23,667 --> 00:08:25,792
similar to the Romulan
cloaking device

155
00:08:25,792 --> 00:08:27,917
but the implementation
is quite difficult.

156
00:08:30,208 --> 00:08:31,291
WORF:
Captain!

157
00:08:31,291 --> 00:08:32,625
Data, what do you read?

158
00:08:32,625 --> 00:08:35,291
Some sort of
scanning device, sir.

159
00:08:35,291 --> 00:08:36,500
PICARD:
Don't touch him!

160
00:08:36,500 --> 00:08:38,000
This beam is emanating
from Aldea.

161
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:39,959
Shields up. La Forge,
contact Commander Riker.

162
00:08:39,959 --> 00:08:41,000
Worf, check all decks.

163
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:42,583
Shields inoperable, sir.

164
00:08:42,583 --> 00:08:44,625
All decks being probed
in a methodical pattern, sir.

165
00:08:44,625 --> 00:08:45,917
All decks, everywhere--
the entire ship?

166
00:08:45,917 --> 00:08:47,208
DATA:
Aye, sir.

167
00:08:47,208 --> 00:08:48,291
LA FORGE:
Can't reach the Commander--

168
00:08:48,291 --> 00:08:49,458
we're being blocked.

169
00:08:52,583 --> 00:08:55,041
Wesley, are you all right?

170
00:08:57,625 --> 00:09:00,875
It was scary
at first

171
00:09:00,875 --> 00:09:02,667
but I didn't really
feel anything.

172
00:09:02,667 --> 00:09:06,166
WORF:
Sir, similar incidents,
all decks...

173
00:09:06,166 --> 00:09:08,166
but only with the children.

174
00:09:12,208 --> 00:09:15,250
Yes, we are an ancient
power, Commander

175
00:09:15,250 --> 00:09:17,041
but we've suffered for it.

176
00:09:17,041 --> 00:09:18,625
Our history is littered
with the deaths

177
00:09:18,625 --> 00:09:21,250
of those Aldeans who wanted
more and more<i> things.</i>

178
00:09:21,250 --> 00:09:22,792
Nothing was ever enough

179
00:09:22,792 --> 00:09:25,500
so we've evolved a very
simple way of living--

180
00:09:25,500 --> 00:09:29,041
for whatever is
taken, something
is given in return.

181
00:09:29,041 --> 00:09:30,917
That seems
an equitable code.

182
00:09:30,917 --> 00:09:33,500
Hmm, it's brought us peace.

183
00:09:33,500 --> 00:09:37,125
Unfortunately, there are very
few of us left to enjoy it.

184
00:09:37,125 --> 00:09:38,458
Why?

185
00:09:38,458 --> 00:09:41,333
That is part of what
we wish to discuss.

186
00:09:43,792 --> 00:09:47,417
We need help from the Federation
to rebuild our heritage.

187
00:09:47,417 --> 00:09:51,000
We need a younger generation,
strong and healthy

188
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:53,959
following in
the Aldean traditions.

189
00:09:53,959 --> 00:09:55,625
I don't understand.
How can the Federation

190
00:09:55,625 --> 00:09:59,250
help influence<i> your</i> children
in<i> your</i> traditions?

191
00:09:59,250 --> 00:10:01,667
Because we have no children,
Commander.

192
00:10:05,291 --> 00:10:08,667
Rashella was the last child
born on this planet.

193
00:10:11,583 --> 00:10:14,750
And your medical community
can do nothing?

194
00:10:14,750 --> 00:10:18,834
They've tried, Dr. Crusher,
and failed.

195
00:10:18,834 --> 00:10:21,000
Perhaps we can help.

196
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:24,417
Radue, exactly why
were we invited here?

197
00:10:24,417 --> 00:10:25,959
We propose a trade:

198
00:10:25,959 --> 00:10:27,542
one which would solve
our problem

199
00:10:27,542 --> 00:10:29,917
and give something back
to the Federation.

200
00:10:29,917 --> 00:10:33,208
And the nature
of this trade?

201
00:10:33,208 --> 00:10:35,041
We need some of your children.

202
00:10:35,041 --> 00:10:37,083
In payment, we will
give you information

203
00:10:37,083 --> 00:10:39,208
that would take you
centuries to acquire.

204
00:10:42,333 --> 00:10:45,333
That might be acceptable
to some other races

205
00:10:45,333 --> 00:10:51,333
but, uh, humans are unusually
attached to their offspring.

206
00:10:51,333 --> 00:10:54,834
Our children are not for sale
at any price.

207
00:10:54,834 --> 00:10:56,250
RIKER:
We sympathize
with your situation

208
00:10:56,250 --> 00:11:00,458
but what you ask
is not possible.

209
00:11:00,458 --> 00:11:03,250
And that's your final answer?

210
00:11:03,250 --> 00:11:05,542
That's my only answer.

211
00:11:05,542 --> 00:11:06,625
Now, if there's
some other way

212
00:11:06,625 --> 00:11:07,917
that we could
help you...

213
00:11:07,917 --> 00:11:10,792
I'm sorry you are
so intransigent.

214
00:11:14,417 --> 00:11:15,834
(<i> high-pitched tone</i> )

215
00:11:17,834 --> 00:11:19,333
Still no response, sir.

216
00:11:19,333 --> 00:11:20,959
(<i> beeping</i> )

217
00:11:23,500 --> 00:11:25,166
Wesley!

218
00:11:26,500 --> 00:11:28,375
They've taken my son.

219
00:11:41,208 --> 00:11:43,000
Alexandra!

220
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:44,709
Alexandra!

221
00:11:44,709 --> 00:11:46,250
(<i> plucking notes</i> )

222
00:11:48,458 --> 00:11:50,250
(<i> alarm sounding</i> )

223
00:11:50,250 --> 00:11:53,333
Captain, saucer section reports
six more children are gone.

224
00:11:53,333 --> 00:11:54,875
It's the children.

225
00:11:54,875 --> 00:11:56,834
That's why we've
been brought here.

226
00:11:56,834 --> 00:11:58,000
That's what they wanted.

227
00:11:58,000 --> 00:11:59,375
And that's what
they have!

228
00:12:04,333 --> 00:12:05,542
Status?

229
00:12:05,542 --> 00:12:06,750
Aldean shields still up.

230
00:12:06,750 --> 00:12:08,500
Hailing frequencies open;
no response.

231
00:12:08,500 --> 00:12:09,875
Keep trying.

232
00:12:09,875 --> 00:12:11,709
Counselor, you'll have
to gather the parents.

233
00:12:11,709 --> 00:12:13,542
They'll need to speak
to you as well, Captain.

234
00:12:13,542 --> 00:12:16,000
(<i> communications beep</i> )
RADUE:
Captain,

235
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:19,125
your children
are with us.

236
00:12:19,125 --> 00:12:23,500
My word of honor--
no harm will ever come to them.

237
00:12:23,500 --> 00:12:26,667
Harm has already
come to them.

238
00:12:26,667 --> 00:12:28,542
Captain, let us begin
discussions

239
00:12:28,542 --> 00:12:31,083
regarding appropriate
compensation.

240
00:12:31,083 --> 00:12:34,083
Compensation?

241
00:12:34,083 --> 00:12:36,208
You have stolen our children
away from...

242
00:12:36,208 --> 00:12:38,250
away from their classrooms,
away from their bedrooms

243
00:12:38,250 --> 00:12:39,792
and you talk about compensation!

244
00:12:39,792 --> 00:12:41,500
You claim to be
a civilized world

245
00:12:41,500 --> 00:12:44,291
and yet you've just committed
an act of utter barbarity!

246
00:12:44,291 --> 00:12:46,750
Captain, we will continue
these discussions

247
00:12:46,750 --> 00:12:48,375
when you've calmed down.

248
00:12:57,250 --> 00:12:59,917
Wesley, I'm frightened.

249
00:13:01,917 --> 00:13:03,834
I know you
are, Katie--

250
00:13:03,834 --> 00:13:05,583
we all are--

251
00:13:05,583 --> 00:13:07,125
but we're going
to be all right.

252
00:13:07,125 --> 00:13:08,667
Everyone knows
where we are

253
00:13:08,667 --> 00:13:11,208
and no one is
going to hurt you.

254
00:13:11,208 --> 00:13:12,375
I promise.

255
00:13:12,375 --> 00:13:14,000
(<i> door opens</i> )

256
00:13:20,542 --> 00:13:21,667
Greetings

257
00:13:21,667 --> 00:13:23,875
Wesley Crusher.

258
00:13:23,875 --> 00:13:27,041
The Custodian indicated
that you would be the leader.

259
00:13:27,041 --> 00:13:28,875
The Custodian?

260
00:13:28,875 --> 00:13:30,375
Who is The Custodian?

261
00:13:30,375 --> 00:13:33,417
The Custodian is not a person.

262
00:13:33,417 --> 00:13:34,875
RASHELLA:
You have been
brought to Aldea

263
00:13:34,875 --> 00:13:36,417
as our guests.

264
00:13:36,417 --> 00:13:39,625
We'll provide anything
you need or want.

265
00:13:39,625 --> 00:13:41,375
We want to go home.

266
00:13:41,375 --> 00:13:46,875
Wesley, all of you have been
chosen because you are special.

267
00:13:46,875 --> 00:13:48,875
Just ask for
anything you want

268
00:13:48,875 --> 00:13:50,667
and you shall have it.

269
00:14:03,166 --> 00:14:06,291
What's happened to Alexandra
and the other children, Captain?

270
00:14:06,291 --> 00:14:08,333
How are you
getting them back?

271
00:14:08,333 --> 00:14:10,917
Toya, sit down.

272
00:14:10,917 --> 00:14:14,125
Don't give in
to fear.

273
00:14:14,125 --> 00:14:17,917
Now, we all knew
what the risks were
when we signed on

274
00:14:17,917 --> 00:14:20,166
and that's the
choice we made.

275
00:14:20,166 --> 00:14:22,333
Now, Captain Picard will
do everything possible

276
00:14:22,333 --> 00:14:23,959
to bring our
children back.

277
00:14:23,959 --> 00:14:26,458
The Aldeans are anxious
to discuss compensation.

278
00:14:26,458 --> 00:14:27,875
Compensation?

279
00:14:27,875 --> 00:14:29,500
That will buy us time.

280
00:14:29,500 --> 00:14:30,792
I've asked Dr. Crusher

281
00:14:30,792 --> 00:14:32,875
to be involved
in these negotiations

282
00:14:32,875 --> 00:14:35,917
as your representative.

283
00:14:35,917 --> 00:14:39,458
Why were these specific
children taken?

284
00:14:39,458 --> 00:14:41,792
We can't be sure.

285
00:14:41,792 --> 00:14:47,000
We do know the Aldeans can't
have children of their own.

286
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:50,458
Then they won't
let them go easily.

287
00:14:50,458 --> 00:14:54,166
I won't insult you by pretending
that any of this will be easy.

288
00:14:54,166 --> 00:14:56,875
But I can tell you
that the<i> Enterprise</i>

289
00:14:56,875 --> 00:15:00,083
will not leave them behind.

290
00:15:00,083 --> 00:15:01,750
You can be assured of that.

291
00:15:03,875 --> 00:15:05,875
Can we talk
with our children

292
00:15:05,875 --> 00:15:08,000
give them some
reassurance

293
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:09,375
let them know
that we are here

294
00:15:09,375 --> 00:15:11,500
and that they
will be safe?

295
00:15:11,500 --> 00:15:13,542
I'll do my best
to arrange that.

296
00:15:16,041 --> 00:15:19,959
The last time I saw him,
I yelled at him.

297
00:15:34,083 --> 00:15:35,667
There you are!

298
00:15:35,667 --> 00:15:37,458
I have you now!

299
00:15:41,542 --> 00:15:42,583
Come in.

300
00:15:42,583 --> 00:15:44,041
Don't be alarmed.

301
00:15:44,041 --> 00:15:46,208
The other children have been
assigned to their units.

302
00:15:46,208 --> 00:15:47,709
Units?

303
00:15:47,709 --> 00:15:50,417
A unit is a group
where those of similar talents

304
00:15:50,417 --> 00:15:53,417
and interests live together.

305
00:15:53,417 --> 00:15:55,125
Do you mean
like a family?

306
00:15:55,125 --> 00:16:00,375
RADUE:
Yes, you could
call it that.

307
00:16:00,375 --> 00:16:02,709
We already
have families.

308
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:07,125
Does Captain Picard
know you're doing this?

309
00:16:07,125 --> 00:16:09,041
We keep nothing
from him.

310
00:16:12,166 --> 00:16:15,625
We've been waiting
for you so long, Harry.

311
00:16:15,625 --> 00:16:18,667
We are artists,
just like you.

312
00:16:18,667 --> 00:16:22,166
We see within you the potential
of what you can be.

313
00:16:22,166 --> 00:16:24,083
I'm not an artist.

314
00:16:24,083 --> 00:16:25,667
You will be

315
00:16:25,667 --> 00:16:27,667
and a great one.

316
00:16:27,667 --> 00:16:29,417
This way, Harry.

317
00:16:37,166 --> 00:16:39,250
Unit B, three, seven, five.

318
00:16:41,667 --> 00:16:43,333
Katie.

319
00:16:45,875 --> 00:16:48,041
I am honored.

320
00:16:48,041 --> 00:16:49,458
Thank you.

321
00:16:49,458 --> 00:16:52,625
Melian is the foremost
musician on Aldea.

322
00:16:52,625 --> 00:16:55,250
Music speaks
its own language.

323
00:16:55,250 --> 00:16:56,834
I know we'll have
much to learn

324
00:16:56,834 --> 00:16:59,208
from each other.

325
00:16:59,208 --> 00:17:00,291
Don't worry, Katie.

326
00:17:00,291 --> 00:17:02,041
You'll be seeing
Wesley soon.

327
00:17:07,917 --> 00:17:09,709
What about me?

328
00:17:09,709 --> 00:17:11,500
Don't I get
a say in this?

329
00:17:11,500 --> 00:17:14,041
Wesley, sometimes
something happens

330
00:17:14,041 --> 00:17:18,500
which you just must accept.

331
00:17:18,500 --> 00:17:19,667
You and the
other children

332
00:17:19,667 --> 00:17:21,083
are now members
of this society.

333
00:17:21,083 --> 00:17:23,375
That will not change.

334
00:17:23,375 --> 00:17:25,208
It is up to you
to make the transition

335
00:17:25,208 --> 00:17:27,000
as easy as possible
for the others.

336
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:30,500
It's your duty,
because you are their leader.

337
00:17:30,500 --> 00:17:33,166
Help them to accept it.

338
00:17:33,166 --> 00:17:34,583
Because nothing you

339
00:17:34,583 --> 00:17:39,000
or those on the starship
can do can change it.

340
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:45,333
Because, like you,
we also have no choice.

341
00:17:48,166 --> 00:17:50,625
(<i> laughter</i> )

342
00:17:50,625 --> 00:17:52,041
Where have you
been, Rashella?

343
00:17:52,041 --> 00:17:54,583
Zena and Aran
are waiting to
take Alexandra.

344
00:17:54,583 --> 00:17:55,959
No.

345
00:17:55,959 --> 00:17:57,709
No? I told you that she...

346
00:17:57,709 --> 00:17:59,291
No, Radue.

347
00:17:59,291 --> 00:18:01,667
They can't have her.

348
00:18:01,667 --> 00:18:03,834
I will never let her go.

349
00:18:12,125 --> 00:18:13,792
Any response from Aldea,
Lieutenant?

350
00:18:13,792 --> 00:18:15,166
Not yet, sir.

351
00:18:15,166 --> 00:18:19,083
Captain, Data has found
something interesting.

352
00:18:19,083 --> 00:18:22,458
The Aldean shield
gives evidence of
random fluctuations

353
00:18:22,458 --> 00:18:25,125
weakening its structure
in isolated sections.

354
00:18:25,125 --> 00:18:26,166
Are you saying
that there are holes

355
00:18:26,166 --> 00:18:27,166
in their defense system?

356
00:18:27,166 --> 00:18:28,583
In essence, yes.

357
00:18:28,583 --> 00:18:31,166
I find it surprising that
after all these eons

358
00:18:31,166 --> 00:18:33,667
the Aldeans have
not perfected
their technology.

359
00:18:33,667 --> 00:18:34,750
One would assume,
they'd be aware

360
00:18:34,750 --> 00:18:36,417
of the weakness
and repair it.

361
00:18:36,417 --> 00:18:39,000
Could we beam an away team
through one of those holes?

362
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:40,125
It's a possibility.

363
00:18:40,125 --> 00:18:41,208
It would have to be
perfectly timed

364
00:18:41,208 --> 00:18:42,166
and there's no guarantee.

365
00:18:42,166 --> 00:18:43,333
We may be
more successful

366
00:18:43,333 --> 00:18:44,583
in deciphering
the code they use

367
00:18:44,583 --> 00:18:46,333
to transport through
the magnetic shield.

368
00:18:46,333 --> 00:18:47,667
Can you do that?

369
00:18:47,667 --> 00:18:49,917
DATA:
Eventually, sir.
I am working on it now

370
00:18:49,917 --> 00:18:52,750
but the number
of permutations
is almost endless.

371
00:18:52,750 --> 00:18:54,083
Keep trying.

372
00:18:54,083 --> 00:18:55,583
While he's doing
that, Number One

373
00:18:55,583 --> 00:18:57,417
I want you and La Forge
to try and find some way

374
00:18:57,417 --> 00:18:58,959
of getting through
one of those holes

375
00:18:58,959 --> 00:19:01,166
because... one way
or another

376
00:19:01,166 --> 00:19:03,542
we have got to
get an away team
on the planet

377
00:19:03,542 --> 00:19:05,208
to locate power source
for the shield

378
00:19:05,208 --> 00:19:07,166
and neutralize it.

379
00:19:07,166 --> 00:19:08,750
You're certain
they'll negotiate?

380
00:19:08,750 --> 00:19:10,625
Oh, they'll
negotiate

381
00:19:10,625 --> 00:19:13,208
or they'll call it that.

382
00:19:13,208 --> 00:19:15,166
They've taken
what they want.

383
00:19:15,166 --> 00:19:16,875
Now they'll rationalize it

384
00:19:16,875 --> 00:19:19,792
by throwing us
some sort of bone.

385
00:19:19,792 --> 00:19:22,417
And when we don't
accept their offer?

386
00:19:22,417 --> 00:19:23,959
The minute that they believe
that we won't accept

387
00:19:23,959 --> 00:19:25,542
their compensation
for the children

388
00:19:25,542 --> 00:19:26,750
they'll break off
the discussion

389
00:19:26,750 --> 00:19:29,375
they'll disappear
behind their shield

390
00:19:29,375 --> 00:19:32,667
locking us out,
and the children in--

391
00:19:32,667 --> 00:19:35,542
forever.

392
00:19:35,542 --> 00:19:37,625
That's why I've got
to keep them talking.

393
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:55,750
Custodian.

394
00:19:55,750 --> 00:19:58,750
Wesley Crusher's voice
will be entered

395
00:19:58,750 --> 00:20:02,375
into the authorized file
for third-level clearance.

396
00:20:02,375 --> 00:20:03,959
CUSTODIAN:
Proceed, Duana.

397
00:20:03,959 --> 00:20:07,750
Announce yourself
to The Custodian.

398
00:20:07,750 --> 00:20:09,166
Hello, Custodian.

399
00:20:09,166 --> 00:20:10,417
I am Wesley Crusher.

400
00:20:10,417 --> 00:20:11,959
Hello, Wesley.

401
00:20:11,959 --> 00:20:15,917
Your voice will now activate
third-level clearance.

402
00:20:15,917 --> 00:20:17,583
What does that mean?

403
00:20:17,583 --> 00:20:20,583
You may ask any
questions you wish.

404
00:20:20,583 --> 00:20:22,291
Thank you.

405
00:20:22,291 --> 00:20:25,000
Duana, what does
The Custodian do?

406
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:26,834
It frees us from all burden.

407
00:20:26,834 --> 00:20:28,709
It takes care of all our needs.

408
00:20:28,709 --> 00:20:30,959
It regulates our lives.

409
00:20:30,959 --> 00:20:32,125
Who built it?

410
00:20:32,125 --> 00:20:33,250
The progenitors.

411
00:20:33,250 --> 00:20:34,375
When?

412
00:20:34,375 --> 00:20:37,417
Oh, hundreds of centuries ago.

413
00:20:37,417 --> 00:20:39,542
What is its power source?

414
00:20:39,542 --> 00:20:41,750
Wesley, why is
that important?

415
00:20:41,750 --> 00:20:44,333
It does what
we ask it to;
it always has.

416
00:20:44,333 --> 00:20:47,458
What difference
does it make
how it works?

417
00:20:47,458 --> 00:20:48,583
If you don't know
how it works

418
00:20:48,583 --> 00:20:50,917
then how can you
repair it?

419
00:20:50,917 --> 00:20:53,333
Why would we want to repair it?

420
00:20:53,333 --> 00:20:55,834
From time to time,
every computer...

421
00:20:55,834 --> 00:20:59,250
I mean, Custodian,
requires maintenance.

422
00:20:59,250 --> 00:21:01,542
Wesley, Radue is right.

423
00:21:01,542 --> 00:21:05,041
You ask questions
I can't answer.

424
00:21:05,041 --> 00:21:09,542
Ask The Custodian
instead.

425
00:21:09,542 --> 00:21:11,625
Custodian

426
00:21:11,625 --> 00:21:13,458
can you show me
where Harry is?

427
00:21:13,458 --> 00:21:15,125
Yes.

428
00:21:15,125 --> 00:21:17,166
Custodian,
show me Harry.

429
00:21:17,166 --> 00:21:18,583
(<i> Custodian beeps</i> )

430
00:21:23,375 --> 00:21:26,250
(<i> instrument buzzing</i> )

431
00:21:28,166 --> 00:21:29,583
I never
did this before.

432
00:21:29,583 --> 00:21:30,625
It's fun.

433
00:21:30,625 --> 00:21:32,875
(<i> laughs</i> )

434
00:21:32,875 --> 00:21:35,667
You are going to make him
into a sculptor?

435
00:21:35,667 --> 00:21:37,250
He already is.

436
00:21:37,250 --> 00:21:39,667
He was just never
encouraged properly.

437
00:21:39,667 --> 00:21:41,041
The tool Leda
is giving him

438
00:21:41,041 --> 00:21:44,959
will allow him
to bring out
his visions.

439
00:21:44,959 --> 00:21:47,000
It will take him years
to learn to do that.

440
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:48,542
Oh, no

441
00:21:48,542 --> 00:21:50,125
it will happen
quite quickly.

442
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:55,625
Custodian,
show me Alexandra.

443
00:21:55,625 --> 00:21:58,000
(<i> beeps</i> )

444
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:01,083
(<i> laughs</i> )

445
00:22:01,083 --> 00:22:02,166
Yeah.

446
00:22:02,166 --> 00:22:03,792
(<i> laughs</i> )

447
00:22:05,625 --> 00:22:07,458
Custodian, show me Mason.

448
00:22:07,458 --> 00:22:08,625
Stop, Custodian.

449
00:22:08,625 --> 00:22:09,959
We must work now.

450
00:22:09,959 --> 00:22:11,625
There's much to learn.

451
00:22:15,083 --> 00:22:16,709
What's in there?

452
00:22:18,750 --> 00:22:20,583
The power source?

453
00:22:23,250 --> 00:22:25,959
I don't know.

454
00:22:25,959 --> 00:22:27,625
<i>Captain's Log, supplemental:</i>

455
00:22:27,625 --> 00:22:30,083
<i>We remain in orbit</i>
<i>around Aldea.</i>

456
00:22:30,083 --> 00:22:31,834
<i>It's becoming all too evident</i>

457
00:22:31,834 --> 00:22:35,291
<i>that talk will not effect</i>
<i>the return of our children.</i>

458
00:22:35,291 --> 00:22:37,834
<i>We must neutralize</i>
<i>the Aldean shield.</i>

459
00:22:37,834 --> 00:22:39,834
<i>Until then,</i>
<i>we are helpless.</i>

460
00:22:39,834 --> 00:22:42,875
Sir, Radue
is hailing us.

461
00:22:42,875 --> 00:22:44,000
(<i> communications beep</i> )

462
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:45,375
RADUE:
Captain Picard.

463
00:22:45,375 --> 00:22:48,250
Dr. Crusher and I
are ready, Radue.

464
00:22:48,250 --> 00:22:50,000
Are you ill, Captain?

465
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:52,375
No, Doctor Crusher
is a staff officer.

466
00:22:52,375 --> 00:22:55,041
Starfleet Regulation 6.57
requires that at least

467
00:22:55,041 --> 00:22:56,458
two staff officers are present

468
00:22:56,458 --> 00:22:58,667
during any treaty
or contract negotiations.

469
00:23:02,083 --> 00:23:03,291
Very well.

470
00:23:03,291 --> 00:23:05,125
(<i> communications beep</i> )

471
00:23:05,125 --> 00:23:06,917
Not much on
pleasantries, is he?

472
00:23:06,917 --> 00:23:10,917
Captain, I am not aware
of Regulation 6.57.

473
00:23:10,917 --> 00:23:12,542
No, Data, neither am I.

474
00:23:12,542 --> 00:23:14,125
I see, sir.

475
00:23:14,125 --> 00:23:18,500
Oh, I see, sir.

476
00:23:18,500 --> 00:23:20,542
Dr. Crusher,
please report to the Bridge.

477
00:23:20,542 --> 00:23:22,375
Now we'll see
what they have in mind.

478
00:23:25,291 --> 00:23:28,000
(<i> electrical whine</i> )

479
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:29,333
Before we begin

480
00:23:29,333 --> 00:23:30,959
we want to see
the children.

481
00:23:30,959 --> 00:23:34,500
No, we're here to negotiate
appropriate compensation

482
00:23:34,500 --> 00:23:36,166
not to pander to emotions.

483
00:23:36,166 --> 00:23:37,959
Please, sit.

484
00:23:42,041 --> 00:23:43,959
We do not condone
your actions.

485
00:23:43,959 --> 00:23:46,000
You're attempting to
salve your conscience

486
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:47,000
by offering us goods

487
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:48,208
in exchange for
our children.

488
00:23:48,208 --> 00:23:50,000
Why do you want
them back so badly?

489
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:51,917
<i>You</i> can always
have more.

490
00:23:51,917 --> 00:23:55,291
You're trifling with
the primal instincts
of our species.

491
00:23:55,291 --> 00:23:57,709
I must warn you
that human parents

492
00:23:57,709 --> 00:23:59,709
are quite willing to die
for their children.

493
00:23:59,709 --> 00:24:02,625
Returning the children
is nonnegotiable.

494
00:24:02,625 --> 00:24:06,291
I promise you, they will have
a beautiful life with us

495
00:24:06,291 --> 00:24:08,667
and they'll be father and mother
to a new breed

496
00:24:08,667 --> 00:24:11,041
born of an ancient culture.

497
00:24:11,041 --> 00:24:14,709
But how can you be so sure
that<i> they</i> can have children?

498
00:24:14,709 --> 00:24:15,834
You can't.

499
00:24:15,834 --> 00:24:17,291
But they<i> will.</i>

500
00:24:17,291 --> 00:24:18,750
Our inability to bear children

501
00:24:18,750 --> 00:24:20,041
is a genetic dysfunction.

502
00:24:20,041 --> 00:24:21,667
It's not
contagious.

503
00:24:26,166 --> 00:24:30,500
We sympathize
with your situation.

504
00:24:30,500 --> 00:24:32,000
Surely, there is a solution

505
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:34,709
that can be
mutually satisfactory.

506
00:24:34,709 --> 00:24:36,917
For us, the problem
is solved

507
00:24:36,917 --> 00:24:38,750
and we're offering you
information

508
00:24:38,750 --> 00:24:42,208
on areas of the galaxy
you do not even know exist.

509
00:24:42,208 --> 00:24:43,750
What more can we offer?

510
00:24:43,750 --> 00:24:47,500
What more
would you like?

511
00:24:47,500 --> 00:24:50,166
A significant beginning

512
00:24:50,166 --> 00:24:52,125
but first, I must ask
that Dr. Crusher

513
00:24:52,125 --> 00:24:54,959
be allowed to see her son
before we continue.

514
00:24:54,959 --> 00:24:57,959
(<i> laughter</i> )

515
00:24:59,375 --> 00:25:03,125
Oh, you are a stubborn people.

516
00:25:03,125 --> 00:25:07,667
Ah, well, that too can be
a positive trait.

517
00:25:10,500 --> 00:25:12,000
You may see him.

518
00:25:14,333 --> 00:25:15,583
Mom!

519
00:25:15,583 --> 00:25:16,917
Wes.

520
00:25:16,917 --> 00:25:19,375
(<i> clicking</i> )

521
00:25:19,375 --> 00:25:21,208
I knew Captain Picard
would get us home.

522
00:25:21,208 --> 00:25:23,083
Not yet, Wes.

523
00:25:24,875 --> 00:25:26,542
Oh.

524
00:25:26,542 --> 00:25:28,250
Are you okay?

525
00:25:28,250 --> 00:25:30,709
And the others?

526
00:25:30,709 --> 00:25:34,333
Okay, really okay.

527
00:25:34,333 --> 00:25:36,291
We've been assigned
to our units--

528
00:25:36,291 --> 00:25:37,959
like families.

529
00:25:41,083 --> 00:25:42,417
They're treating us
like gods.

530
00:25:42,417 --> 00:25:44,083
(<i> laughs</i> )

531
00:25:44,083 --> 00:25:47,625
Well, don't let it
go to your head.

532
00:25:47,625 --> 00:25:48,959
I won't.

533
00:25:48,959 --> 00:25:50,625
(<i> door opening</i> )

534
00:25:54,625 --> 00:25:55,834
Wes seems fine.

535
00:25:55,834 --> 00:25:57,625
He says the other
children are, too.

536
00:25:57,625 --> 00:25:59,250
Of course
they're well.

537
00:25:59,250 --> 00:26:01,417
Captain Picard,
you have our offer.

538
00:26:01,417 --> 00:26:03,000
It is final.

539
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:04,333
Rashella.

540
00:26:05,458 --> 00:26:09,166
(<i> electrical whine</i> )

541
00:26:09,166 --> 00:26:10,166
(<i> communications beep</i> )

542
00:26:10,166 --> 00:26:12,000
RADUE:
Captain.

543
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:15,250
We want you to understand
the nature of your choice.

544
00:26:17,208 --> 00:26:20,417
A small demonstration
of our power.

545
00:26:21,792 --> 00:26:23,000
(<i> whooshing</i> )

546
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:24,333
(<i> thundering</i> )

547
00:26:24,333 --> 00:26:26,417
(<i> alarm sounding</i> )

548
00:26:26,417 --> 00:26:28,333
(<i> roaring</i> )

549
00:26:28,333 --> 00:26:31,375
(<i> alarm sounding</i> )

550
00:26:31,375 --> 00:26:33,750
(<i> roaring subsides</i> )

551
00:26:36,667 --> 00:26:38,959
(<i> alarm continuing</i> )

552
00:26:38,959 --> 00:26:40,208
What was that?

553
00:26:40,208 --> 00:26:42,333
I believe it was
a repulsor beam.

554
00:26:42,333 --> 00:26:43,625
Position report.

555
00:26:43,625 --> 00:26:45,291
This is unbelievable, sir.

556
00:26:45,291 --> 00:26:48,625
According to my calculations,
we're three days from Aldea.

557
00:26:50,542 --> 00:26:52,000
At warp nine.

558
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:56,000
And they call that
a "small demonstration"?

559
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:58,458
Geordi, get us back to Aldea--
warp nine.

560
00:26:58,458 --> 00:26:59,458
Aye, sir.
(<i> communications beep</i> )

561
00:26:59,458 --> 00:27:00,917
RADUE:
Captain--

562
00:27:00,917 --> 00:27:03,083
if you don't accept our terms

563
00:27:03,083 --> 00:27:05,875
the<i> Enterprise</i> will be pushed
so far away

564
00:27:05,875 --> 00:27:07,417
that by the time you return

565
00:27:07,417 --> 00:27:10,375
your children
will be grandparents.

566
00:27:17,875 --> 00:27:21,208
<i>Captain's Log,</i>
<i>Stardate 41512.4:</i>

567
00:27:21,208 --> 00:27:24,959
<i>We are 20 hours away from Aldea</i>
<i>and no closer to a solution.</i>

568
00:27:24,959 --> 00:27:27,625
<i>Their deliberate show of force</i>
<i>pushed us out of orbit</i>

569
00:27:27,625 --> 00:27:29,667
<i>and could've easily</i>
<i>disintegrated the ship.</i>

570
00:27:34,625 --> 00:27:37,000
Now hold it a little bit
more firmly.

571
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:39,250
That's it-- perfect.

572
00:27:39,250 --> 00:27:40,917
Now, think...

573
00:27:40,917 --> 00:27:43,375
No, think's not right.

574
00:27:43,375 --> 00:27:46,000
<i>Feel</i> the notes
inside your head.

575
00:27:55,125 --> 00:27:56,417
(<i> musical discord</i> )

576
00:27:56,417 --> 00:27:57,750
Sorry!

577
00:27:57,750 --> 00:27:58,834
Did I break it?

578
00:27:58,834 --> 00:28:00,041
No, it's all right.

579
00:28:00,041 --> 00:28:02,333
You can't break this.

580
00:28:02,333 --> 00:28:06,041
Did, did exactly
what I thought...

581
00:28:06,041 --> 00:28:07,542
I mean, felt.

582
00:28:07,542 --> 00:28:10,500
Yes, it's a direct reflection
of the music within.

583
00:28:10,500 --> 00:28:13,625
Now we have to teach you
to structure that feeling.

584
00:28:13,625 --> 00:28:15,125
Try it again.

585
00:28:20,125 --> 00:28:25,250
(<i> melancholy tune plays</i> )

586
00:28:43,875 --> 00:28:47,208
That was beautiful.

587
00:28:47,208 --> 00:28:49,709
Now...

588
00:28:49,709 --> 00:28:53,250
play something happier.

589
00:28:53,250 --> 00:28:55,291
That's not
the way I feel.

590
00:28:59,208 --> 00:29:03,000
I don't want to
do this anymore.

591
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:04,875
(<i> instrument buzzing</i> )

592
00:29:06,917 --> 00:29:08,250
You see, Harry?

593
00:29:08,250 --> 00:29:10,750
I told you, you were
going to be an artist.

594
00:29:10,750 --> 00:29:12,291
Are you sure?

595
00:29:12,291 --> 00:29:13,583
Did I really do this?

596
00:29:13,583 --> 00:29:14,917
Oh, yes.

597
00:29:14,917 --> 00:29:17,417
Your talent
has always been there.

598
00:29:17,417 --> 00:29:20,750
The sculpting tool is just
helping you develop it.

599
00:29:20,750 --> 00:29:23,625
It's what you were
meant to do.

600
00:29:23,625 --> 00:29:26,250
You mean, I don't have
to take calculus anymore?

601
00:29:26,250 --> 00:29:27,500
You don't have
to do anything

602
00:29:27,500 --> 00:29:30,500
you don't want to.

603
00:29:30,500 --> 00:29:31,917
What's calculus?

604
00:29:31,917 --> 00:29:33,709
Nothing important.

605
00:29:33,709 --> 00:29:36,917
Can I do some more?

606
00:29:36,917 --> 00:29:38,709
(<i> instrument buzzing</i> )

607
00:29:40,667 --> 00:29:42,542
<i>Captain's Log, supplemental:</i>

608
00:29:42,542 --> 00:29:46,041
<i>It has been three days since</i>
<i>the Aldeans pushed us away.</i>

609
00:29:46,041 --> 00:29:50,333
<i>We have had no contact</i>
<i>with Radue since then.</i>

610
00:29:50,333 --> 00:29:52,333
Open hailing frequencies,
Lieutenant Yar.

611
00:29:52,333 --> 00:29:53,458
(<i> communications beep</i> )

612
00:29:53,458 --> 00:29:56,250
Frequencies open, sir.

613
00:29:56,250 --> 00:29:57,417
Radue, this is Picard.

614
00:29:57,417 --> 00:29:58,542
(<i> communications beep</i> )

615
00:29:58,542 --> 00:29:59,709
Welcome back, Captain.

616
00:29:59,709 --> 00:30:01,125
What have you decided?

617
00:30:01,125 --> 00:30:05,333
That there is room
for discussion, Radue.

618
00:30:05,333 --> 00:30:07,959
We will bring you down
when we're ready.

619
00:30:07,959 --> 00:30:09,875
(<i> communications beep</i> )

620
00:30:09,875 --> 00:30:11,875
Data, find a way
to defeat that shield.

621
00:30:11,875 --> 00:30:13,291
That may be
impossible, sir.

622
00:30:13,291 --> 00:30:15,083
Things are only impossible
until they're not.

623
00:30:15,083 --> 00:30:16,333
Yes, sir.

624
00:30:18,959 --> 00:30:20,542
Captain...

625
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:24,458
...here's what
I've learned so far.

626
00:30:24,458 --> 00:30:25,875
Duana is dying.

627
00:30:25,875 --> 00:30:27,125
I have no reason
to believe

628
00:30:27,125 --> 00:30:28,875
the other Aldeans
are any healthier.

629
00:30:28,875 --> 00:30:31,750
They're suffering from
a kind of chromosomal damage.

630
00:30:31,750 --> 00:30:34,208
It could be genetic
or environmental.

631
00:30:34,208 --> 00:30:35,625
And is that why
they can't conceive?

632
00:30:35,625 --> 00:30:38,041
Yes. It also explains
their lack of appetite

633
00:30:38,041 --> 00:30:41,875
extreme pallor
and sensitivity to light.

634
00:30:41,875 --> 00:30:45,291
An entire civilization
that's terminally ill.

635
00:30:45,291 --> 00:30:47,291
Is it reversible?

636
00:30:47,291 --> 00:30:49,750
I won't know
until I find the cause

637
00:30:49,750 --> 00:30:51,083
and you don't need
to tell me--

638
00:30:51,083 --> 00:30:53,625
time is running out.

639
00:30:53,625 --> 00:30:55,125
Good work, Doctor.

640
00:31:03,125 --> 00:31:05,000
Have the lesions gone?

641
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:06,375
Yes.

642
00:31:06,375 --> 00:31:08,250
The medicine
worked again.

643
00:31:08,250 --> 00:31:09,834
Good.

644
00:31:09,834 --> 00:31:11,625
Come see what
Harry's doing.

645
00:31:17,959 --> 00:31:19,834
Beautiful!

646
00:31:19,834 --> 00:31:20,959
Yeah.

647
00:31:20,959 --> 00:31:23,458
It really turned out well.

648
00:31:23,458 --> 00:31:25,792
It's so alive
and graceful.

649
00:31:25,792 --> 00:31:26,959
What do you call it?

650
00:31:26,959 --> 00:31:28,542
It's a dolphin.

651
00:31:28,542 --> 00:31:29,875
LEDA:
Dolphin?

652
00:31:29,875 --> 00:31:31,917
You know,
it swims in the ocean--

653
00:31:31,917 --> 00:31:35,166
like a fish,
only it's not a fish.

654
00:31:35,166 --> 00:31:38,750
Ah, a fish!

655
00:31:38,750 --> 00:31:41,500
We used to have those
in our oceans.

656
00:31:41,500 --> 00:31:43,875
I've never seen
one before.

657
00:31:43,875 --> 00:31:45,542
I used to live near the ocean

658
00:31:45,542 --> 00:31:46,709
on Zadar IV.

659
00:31:46,709 --> 00:31:48,458
My dad's an oceanographer.

660
00:31:48,458 --> 00:31:50,458
He says that, well...

661
00:31:53,667 --> 00:31:55,333
...never mind.

662
00:31:55,333 --> 00:31:57,417
It... it doesn't matter.

663
00:32:07,041 --> 00:32:09,542
(<i> humming softly</i> )

664
00:32:09,542 --> 00:32:11,000
Shh, shh.

665
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:12,792
I want Mommy.

666
00:32:12,792 --> 00:32:14,000
Shh, shh...

667
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:17,750
I want Mommy.
Shh...

668
00:32:17,750 --> 00:32:20,583
You haven't eaten.

669
00:32:20,583 --> 00:32:22,291
<i>You</i> didn't
eat anything.

670
00:32:22,291 --> 00:32:24,291
We need very little.

671
00:32:24,291 --> 00:32:26,375
We know you
miss your family

672
00:32:26,375 --> 00:32:28,625
but you'll grow
accustomed to us.

673
00:32:28,625 --> 00:32:30,500
I promise you'll be happy.

674
00:32:30,500 --> 00:32:33,041
We were happy before we came.

675
00:32:33,041 --> 00:32:35,834
We are offering more,
especially for you.

676
00:32:39,959 --> 00:32:42,458
Duana...

677
00:32:42,458 --> 00:32:45,959
I feel badly for you
that you have no children

678
00:32:45,959 --> 00:32:47,542
but I have
to tell you

679
00:32:47,542 --> 00:32:50,750
that we don't want to be here

680
00:32:50,750 --> 00:32:52,583
and we will not cooperate.

681
00:33:07,458 --> 00:33:08,792
Custodian's room.

682
00:33:20,542 --> 00:33:23,083
(<i> whispering</i> ):
Custodian, this
is Wesley Crusher.

683
00:33:23,083 --> 00:33:24,125
Proceed, Wesley.

684
00:33:24,125 --> 00:33:27,667
Shh!

685
00:33:27,667 --> 00:33:29,291
Show me where
the<i> Enterprise</i>
children are

686
00:33:29,291 --> 00:33:30,792
in relation
to this room.

687
00:33:30,792 --> 00:33:34,458
(<i> beeps</i> )

688
00:33:34,458 --> 00:33:35,917
Thank you.

689
00:33:35,917 --> 00:33:37,083
Good night.

690
00:33:37,083 --> 00:33:39,875
Good night, Wesley.
(<i> beeps</i> )

691
00:33:51,709 --> 00:33:52,834
(<i> gasps</i> )

692
00:33:52,834 --> 00:33:54,750
Shh!

693
00:33:54,750 --> 00:33:56,959
(<i> whispering</i> ):
I think I know a
way to get us home.

694
00:33:56,959 --> 00:34:00,583
I need your help.

695
00:34:00,583 --> 00:34:04,667
<i>Chief Medical Officer's Log,</i>
<i>Stardate 41512.9:</i>

696
00:34:04,667 --> 00:34:06,000
<i>I've begun to suspect</i>

697
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:07,917
<i>that whatever</i>
<i>is killing the Aldeans</i>

698
00:34:07,917 --> 00:34:12,458
<i>is related to a danger faced</i>
<i>by Earth in the 21st century.</i>

699
00:34:12,458 --> 00:34:14,250
<i>Can it be</i>
<i>that Aldea's ozone layer</i>

700
00:34:14,250 --> 00:34:17,667
<i>has been weakened?</i>

701
00:34:17,667 --> 00:34:22,125
KATIE:
Why will not talking or eating
make them send us home?

702
00:34:22,125 --> 00:34:24,917
It's called
passive resistance.

703
00:34:24,917 --> 00:34:28,458
We don't do
what they want us to do

704
00:34:28,458 --> 00:34:30,125
and they
won't want us.

705
00:34:30,125 --> 00:34:31,667
Will they
get mad at us?

706
00:34:31,667 --> 00:34:33,625
WESLEY:
They won't
hurt us.

707
00:34:33,625 --> 00:34:37,291
But, Wes, I do kind
of like them.

708
00:34:37,291 --> 00:34:38,750
So do I

709
00:34:38,750 --> 00:34:42,125
but I don't want to stay here
forever, do you?

710
00:34:42,125 --> 00:34:44,041
No.

711
00:34:44,041 --> 00:34:46,667
But I like working
with the wood.

712
00:34:46,667 --> 00:34:48,291
WESLEY:
Harry...

713
00:34:48,291 --> 00:34:50,291
we all have to be
in this together

714
00:34:50,291 --> 00:34:53,917
or it's not going to work.

715
00:34:53,917 --> 00:34:56,625
Okay.

716
00:34:56,625 --> 00:34:58,000
I'll do it.

717
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:00,041
What are you all doing here
together?

718
00:35:06,750 --> 00:35:08,583
What is
going on here?

719
00:35:14,875 --> 00:35:16,750
(<i> console beeping</i> )

720
00:35:18,125 --> 00:35:19,667
I've got it, Captain.

721
00:35:19,667 --> 00:35:20,667
The Aldeans
are suffering

722
00:35:20,667 --> 00:35:22,750
from radiation
poisoning.

723
00:35:22,750 --> 00:35:23,792
Is that what made
them sterile?

724
00:35:23,792 --> 00:35:24,834
Yes.

725
00:35:24,834 --> 00:35:26,041
Is it
reversible?

726
00:35:26,041 --> 00:35:27,208
With proper
treatment, yes.

727
00:35:27,208 --> 00:35:29,959
DATA:
Captain
Sir.

728
00:35:29,959 --> 00:35:32,458
These permutations are going
to take a very long time.

729
00:35:32,458 --> 00:35:33,417
How long?

730
00:35:33,417 --> 00:35:34,542
Weeks.

731
00:35:34,542 --> 00:35:35,875
RIKER:
There is
the other option.

732
00:35:35,875 --> 00:35:37,041
LA FORGE:
We were able
to further define

733
00:35:37,041 --> 00:35:38,792
the weakness
in their shield.

734
00:35:38,792 --> 00:35:41,875
It's not so much a hole
as it is a fluctuation.

735
00:35:41,875 --> 00:35:43,208
If the timing is
precise, it is possible

736
00:35:43,208 --> 00:35:44,875
to beam through
and onto the planet.

737
00:35:44,875 --> 00:35:46,875
Why don't we just beam the
children up through the hole?

738
00:35:46,875 --> 00:35:50,041
The timing would be more
difficult and the risk greater.

739
00:35:50,041 --> 00:35:51,417
All right,
you and Data beam down.

740
00:35:51,417 --> 00:35:52,583
Locate the power source
of that shield.

741
00:35:52,583 --> 00:35:54,041
Knock it out.

742
00:35:54,041 --> 00:35:57,417
I'll, uh, delay the Aldeans
till you're ready.

743
00:35:59,083 --> 00:36:02,041
(<i> giggling</i> )

744
00:36:02,041 --> 00:36:03,500
Shh.

745
00:36:07,208 --> 00:36:09,125
Will you
at least eat?

746
00:36:24,917 --> 00:36:26,500
No, Alexandra.

747
00:36:26,500 --> 00:36:28,458
Why?

748
00:36:28,458 --> 00:36:30,125
We can't eat.

749
00:36:30,125 --> 00:36:31,125
I know
you're hungry--

750
00:36:31,125 --> 00:36:33,083
we all are--

751
00:36:33,083 --> 00:36:34,583
but it's our way
of telling them

752
00:36:34,583 --> 00:36:36,542
that we want to go home.

753
00:36:36,542 --> 00:36:37,542
Understand?

754
00:36:37,542 --> 00:36:38,875
Yeah.

755
00:36:45,208 --> 00:36:46,333
(<i> communications beep</i> )

756
00:36:46,333 --> 00:36:47,542
We're ready,
Lieutenant Worf.

757
00:36:49,875 --> 00:36:51,417
RADUE:
Captain

758
00:36:51,417 --> 00:36:54,417
you may come down now
to conclude our discussion

759
00:36:54,417 --> 00:36:57,417
or your ship may leave.

760
00:36:57,417 --> 00:36:59,500
It's your choice.

761
00:36:59,500 --> 00:37:00,709
Dr. Crusher
and I are prepared

762
00:37:00,709 --> 00:37:03,458
to conclude
our negotiations.

763
00:37:03,458 --> 00:37:05,458
(<i> transporter whines)</i>
(<i> communications beep</i> )

764
00:37:05,458 --> 00:37:07,250
Transporter room, now!

765
00:37:07,250 --> 00:37:08,792
(<i> transporter whines</i> )

766
00:37:29,667 --> 00:37:31,375
This is it, Commander.

767
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:43,291
It is programmed
to accept only

768
00:37:43,291 --> 00:37:45,625
authorized voice
command.

769
00:37:45,625 --> 00:37:46,959
There's no way
we can override?

770
00:37:46,959 --> 00:37:49,583
No, but I can
scramble the input

771
00:37:49,583 --> 00:37:51,375
so that nobody
else can.

772
00:37:52,917 --> 00:37:55,417
Before we begin, Captain

773
00:37:55,417 --> 00:37:57,709
you must speak
with the children.

774
00:37:57,709 --> 00:38:00,458
It seems they're
on some sort of "strike"?

775
00:38:00,458 --> 00:38:03,041
I don't-I don't
understand it.

776
00:38:03,041 --> 00:38:05,667
You must deal with this,
Captain.

777
00:38:05,667 --> 00:38:09,542
I'm, uh, not very good
with children.

778
00:38:14,083 --> 00:38:15,917
Strike.

779
00:38:15,917 --> 00:38:18,291
I'll see
what I can do.

